//! Per-language lexer themes — the Phase 4.5 syntax-highlighting table.
//!
//! Lexilla tokenises; it does not colour. Every lexer classifies its
//! input into numbered style slots (`SCE_*`), and the host decides what
//! each slot looks like. This module is that decision, for every
//! language in `core::lang::LANG_TABLE` that has a Lexilla lexer:
//! a [`LangTheme`] per language mapping `SCE_*` indices onto a shared
//! semantic palette ([`StyleSlot`]), plus the keyword classes to install
//! via `SCI_SETKEYWORDS`.
//!
//! # Why this lives in `editor` and not in a UI crate
//!
//! It was originally written inside `ui_win32`, which made it
//! unreachable from any other backend — the GTK build would have had to
//! duplicate ~8000 lines of table to show a single coloured keyword.
//! Nothing here is platform-specific: applying a theme is a sequence of
//! `SCI_STYLESETFORE` / `SCI_SETKEYWORDS` / `SCI_SETPROPERTY` messages,
//! which is exactly what [`EditorHandle`] exists to wrap. Colours are
//! plain `u32` in Scintilla's `0x00BBGGRR` order — the same byte order
//! Win32 calls `COLORREF`, but no Win32 type is involved.
//!
//! `core` would be the wrong home despite this being mostly data: the
//! table is keyed by `SCE_*` constants from `scintilla-sys`, and
//! DESIGN.md §2.1 forbids `core` depending on Scintilla.
//!
//! # Entry points
//!
//! [`apply_lang_theme`] is what backends call on a language switch. The
//! four `apply_*` helpers are exposed separately because Scintilla's
//! `SCI_STYLECLEARALL` resets the predefined 32–39 style range, so a
//! host that touches `STYLE_DEFAULT` itself must re-apply them.
//!
//! # Adding a language
//!
//! Mechanical, and tracked row-by-row in `docs/lexers-coverage.md`:
//!
//! 1. Confirm the lexer's `SCE_*_*` style constants are declared in
//!    `crates/scintilla-sys/src/lib.rs`; new lexers append a batch.
//! 2. Add a `<LANG>_KEYWORDS` const for the primary keyword list (plus
//!    `_KEYWORDS2` / `_KEYWORDS3` if the lexer uses more than one
//!    keyword class). These live in `codepp_core::lang`, not here, so
//!    other tools — test harnesses, a future language inspector — can
//!    reuse them without depending on Scintilla.
//! 3. Build a `<LANG>_STYLES: &[(usize, StyleSlot)]` table mapping each
//!    style index the lexer emits onto a palette slot.
//! 4. Build `<LANG>_ITALIC` / `<LANG>_BOLD` lists for the indices that
//!    want those modifiers — typically comments italic, keywords bold.
//! 5. Build a `<LANG>_THEME: LangTheme` const wiring those together.
//! 6. Add an `else if lang == L_<LANG> { Some(&<LANG>_THEME) }` branch
//!    to [`lang_theme`]. The dispatch is an `if`/`else if` chain rather
//!    than a `match` because `LangType`'s const-pattern story is fiddly
//!    across compiler versions; the chain is explicit and bulletproof.
//! 7. Flip the language's row in `docs/lexers-coverage.md` from 🟡 to ✅.
//!
//! See DESIGN.md §7.2 Phase 4.5 for the binding completion gate.
//!
//! # Allowed pedantic lints, with rationale
//!
//! - `clippy::too_many_lines` — [`lang_theme`] is an 85-arm, ~179-line
//!   dispatch from `LangType` to a theme constant, and several test
//!   functions assert over the whole table. Splitting either into
//!   100-line chunks would fragment one lookup into arbitrary pieces
//!   with no reader benefit.
//! - `clippy::items_after_statements` — the table tests put
//!   scope-local `use` imports next to the assertions that need them
//!   rather than hoisting every one to the top of a long test.
//! - `clippy::similar_names` — the data deliberately pairs names like
//!   `JSON_THEME` / `JSON5_THEME` and `json_entry` / `json5_entry`,
//!   because the languages themselves are near-homonyms.
//!
//! These three are file-level rather than per-item because they follow
//! from the shape of a large data table, which is a structural choice
//! (DESIGN.md §9.3), not an oversight at any one site. They match the
//! allows this code carried in `ui_win32` before the move, so the
//! extraction changes no lint posture.
#![allow(
    clippy::too_many_lines,
    clippy::items_after_statements,
    clippy::similar_names
)]

